# Node.js Server Rules

> Use this layer **only** when something cannot reasonably be done in a Supabase Edge Function (long-running jobs, websockets we control, third-party SDK that doesn't run in Deno, etc.). If unsure, ask before adding code here.

## Framework
- Fastify preferred. Express acceptable if the user already chose it.
- TypeScript strict mode. No JS files in `server/`.

## Structure
```
server/
├── index.ts          # Entry — wires plugins, starts listener
├── routes/           # One file per resource: users.ts, posts.ts
├── middleware/       # Auth, logging, error handler
├── lib/              # Supabase service-role client, third-party clients
└── schemas/          # zod schemas for request validation
```

## Patterns
- Async/await everywhere. No raw `.then()` chains.
- Every route handler validates its body with `zod` before doing anything.
- Every route handler is wrapped in a try/catch that delegates to the central error middleware. Never silently swallow errors.
- Use a request-scoped logger (`pino`) — include a request ID on every log line.

## Security
- Never trust `req.body`, `req.query`, or `req.params` — validate first.
- Verify the Supabase JWT on every protected route. Don't reinvent auth.
- Rate-limit any public endpoint. Default: 60 req/min per IP.
- CORS: explicit allowlist, never `*` in production.
- Service-role Supabase key only used here, read from `process.env`. Never log it.

## Errors
- Throw typed errors (`class HttpError extends Error { status: number }`).
- The central error middleware maps them to JSON responses: `{ error: { code, message } }`.
- 4xx for client mistakes, 5xx for server bugs. Don't return 500 for a missing query param.

## Testing
- Every route has at least one happy-path and one failure-path test in `tests/integration/`.
- Use a separate Supabase project (or local instance) for tests — never the dev DB.
